    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 17 with a lineup anchored by two elite plays against Mart\u00edn P\u00e9rez. **Trea Turner** (81.27) and **Kyle Schwarber** (79.42) represent our highest efficiency ceilings, capitalizing on a favorable matchup against the southpaw that yields a substantial 19% SP skill boost and an ideal #1/#2 order placement. **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (73.14) and **Hyeseong Kim** (70.16) also project as strong starts; **Pete Crow-Armstrong** specifically benefits from a 14% boost due to dynamic platoon splits, though we must keep a close eye on his spot in the order as the #8 hitter limits his overall run-scoring potential. **Yordan Alvarez** remains a core piece with a 64.91 score, providing high-floor production despite a slightly tougher matchup against Kyle Leahy.\n\nThe most difficult decision on today\u2019s board involved **Victor Scott II**, who just missed the cut with a 47.57 score. While **Victor Scott II** offers the elite stolen base upside our strategy prioritizes, the negative pressure from his assumed #9 position in the lineup ultimately tipped the optimizer toward higher-projected hitters like **Jerar Encarnacion** and **Kazuma Okamoto**. We are also closely monitoring **Dillon Dingler**, whose 55.38 score is heavily buoyed by a 14% platoon advantage against Ranger Suarez. While the matchup against a 3.73 xERA arm is risky, **Dillon Dingler** remains in the C2 slot as our most viable option to maximize efficiency behind the dish.\n\nManagement must remain alert to the \"Lineup Pending\" status across the board, particularly for **Gary Sanchez**, **Kazuma Okamoto**, and **Caleb Durbin**. Any unexpected shuffling\u2014specifically if **Caleb Durbin** or **Chase Meidroth** are pushed down the order\u2014will necessitate a re-evaluation of their efficiency scores. While we are comfortable with today's configuration, the volatility of the back-end spots necessitates a quick pivot if official lineups deviate significantly from our current projections.",
